title: Place de la Concorde
description: Built by King Louis XV in the 18th century is one of Paris's most famous squares, This is also the spot were King Louis XVI and Queen Marie Antoinette were beheaded in 1793. The square used to be called Place de la Louis XV but was renamed during the revolution.

title: Parc Clichy-Batignolles - Martin Luther King
description:
L'image est trompeuse, mais à la place de la plupart de ces halles de fret ferroviaire, on trouve aujourd'hui un parc de 4 hectares, en phase d'achèvement : 
- aire de jeux pour les plus de 5-7 ans, 
- aire de jeux pour les petits, 
- skate-parc, 
- éolienne, 
- bassins de récupération des eaux de pluie,
- terrain de basket, 
- terrain de foot en terre battue,
- mur pour les jeux de balle,
- mails,
- bientôt des jets d'eaux sur un sol pavé,
- pelouses
En projet : actuellement de 4,3 ha, il doit voir sa superficie augmenter de 2,5 ha en 2013, pour atteindre finalement 10 ha en 2017 (jusqu'au Bd Berthier). Dans l'immédiat, aménagement de jardin partagé, ainsi que la construction de toilettes en dur et de la loge des gardiens.

title: Residence of the Invalids
description: The National Residence of the Invalids (L'Hôtel national des Invalides) is a complex of buildings in the 7th arrondissement, containing museums and monuments, all relating to the military history of France, as well as a hospital and a retirement home for war veterans, the building's original purpose.

title: Gare Saint-Lazare
description: The second busiest railway station in both France and Europe with over 450,000 passengers a year. There are 27 platforms sorted into six destinations. It is the terminus of a network of lines to Normandy and the suburbs of Paris such as Versailles, known as the Résau St. Lazare. Further out destinations include Le Havre, Caen, Cherbourg, Rouen and Dieppe.

title: Boulevard Haussmann
description: Boulevard Haussmann running from Paris VIIIe to Paris IXe arrondissement, 2.53 km long, is one of the wide tree-lined boulevards driven through Paris during the Second French Empire by Baron Haussmann, who retained the complete confidence of Napoleon III.

title: Palais Royal - Constitutional Council

The Palais Royal (English: Royal Palace) houses the Constitutional Council of France, the Constitutional Council is the highest constitutional authority in France. 
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constitutional_Council_of_France

The Palais Royal also houses the Ministry of Culture and in the south wing the Council of State.
